<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n06051c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n06" href="#n06051c">N06 (VI.B.11)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n06all.htm#n06051c"> 51(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> dice (divination) / form of lingua / fire / numbers / Combel (jeux de barre)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Outre ces jeux qui nous ont transmis le souvenir de l&apos;art de la guerre comme elle se faisait primitivement, Tylor en mentionne un certain nombre qui nous reproduisent de m&ecirc;me, en mani&egrave;re de r&eacute;cr&eacute;ation et de le&ccedil;ons enfantines, les premi&egrave;res pages de l&apos;histoire de ce qu&apos;on peut appeler l&apos;enfance de l&apos;humanit&eacute; (les uns ou les autres rappelant <mark>la formation du langage, de la num&eacute;ration, la production du feu</mark>, etc.), ou bien qui perp&eacute;tuent une branche de la science des sauvages, jadis en grand honneur, <mark>la divination</mark> (pile ou face, <mark>d&eacute;s</mark>, osselets, etc.). Notons que <mark>le jeu de barres est une imitation du Cembel</mark>, cet usage guerrier du moyen &acirc;ge. <font color="green">[In addition to these games which have transmitted to us the memory of the art of war as it was originally done, Tylor mentions a number which reproduce us in the same way, as a way of recreation and childish lessons, the first pages of history of what may be called the childhood of humanity (some recalling the formation of language, numeration, the production of fire, etc.), or which perpetuate a branch of the science of savages once in great honor, divination (coin or face, dice, ossicles, etc.). Note that the busbar is an imitation of the Cembel, this warlike use of the Middle Ages.]</font> <small> Fr&eacute;d&eacute;ric Queyrat, <a name="FQLJ" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#FQLJ"><cite title="source">Les Jeux des Enfants</cite></a> (1920) 82-3f</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
